246
00:14:43,048 --> 00:14:44,133
Order's up.

247
00:14:46,594 --> 00:14:49,054
[inaudible conversation]

248
00:15:04,946 --> 00:15:06,739
[waiter] Enjoy your food.
I think you will all love it.

249
00:15:09,908 --> 00:15:11,119
- That was...
- Jeans!

250
00:15:11,201 --> 00:15:12,787
- Excuse me.
- But also skiing too.

251
00:15:12,870 --> 00:15:14,831
It's-- I don't understand
why he does that everytime.

252
00:15:14,913 --> 00:15:16,749
OK. Sorry, I'll be right back.

253
00:15:16,832 --> 00:15:19,000
- It's not fun.
- Have fun with that.

254
00:15:20,128 --> 00:15:23,255
- [giggling and squealing]
- [glasses clinking]

255
00:15:23,588 --> 00:15:26,341
Hello. I'm the manager here.

256
00:15:26,466 --> 00:15:28,719
I heard you asked to see me.
My name is Clara.

257
00:15:28,802 --> 00:15:31,889
How's everything today?
Can we grab you some more drinks?

258
00:15:31,972 --> 00:15:33,932
[sighs] More drinks!
What a great idea, Claire!

259
00:15:34,015 --> 00:15:35,100
- Oh, It's Clara.
- [Janice] Oh!

260
00:15:35,434 --> 00:15:37,352
- Uh, I'm Janice.
- And I'm the other Janice!

261
00:15:37,727 --> 00:15:40,815
Janice and Janice. Two Janices!
[squeals]

262
00:15:40,898 --> 00:15:44,192
We are just a couple of single girls
on vacation here in the mountains.

263
00:15:44,317 --> 00:15:46,486
And we happened to notice
that your new chef is...

264
00:15:47,028 --> 00:15:49,948
- [both] Shane Roarke!
- Oh, I'm afraid I can't really

265
00:15:50,073 --> 00:15:51,033
be much help. I don't know him

266
00:15:51,116 --> 00:15:52,951
- that well--
- We feel like we know him personally.

267
00:15:54,287 --> 00:15:56,788
So, we were wondering
if you could ask Shane

268
00:15:56,873 --> 00:15:58,206
if he'd like to come out and say hello?

269
00:15:59,250 --> 00:16:02,003
I mean, we would love
to meet him. [chuckles]

270
00:16:02,128 --> 00:16:04,129
Oh, sure. I mean, he's pretty busy...

271
00:16:04,212 --> 00:16:06,506
- Thank you!
- Thanks.

272
00:16:06,756 --> 00:16:08,842
- [glasses clinking]
- [Janice] Shane Roarke. She's gonna get...

273
00:16:09,509 --> 00:16:11,721
- [Clara] Shane! Hi.
- Hi.

274
00:16:12,138 --> 00:16:13,054
Um...

275
00:16:13,889 --> 00:16:15,975
- Hi. Clara. Hi.
- Hi. Clara. Hi.

276
00:16:16,057 --> 00:16:18,602
- Yeah, now, we've officially said hi.
- Yeah, we have.

277
00:16:18,686 --> 00:16:20,897
Um, I'm--I'm really sorry to bother you,

278
00:16:20,980 --> 00:16:22,273
but I have a table of young ladies.

279
00:16:22,355 --> 00:16:24,274
They asked if you could drop by
to say hello.

280
00:16:24,357 --> 00:16:26,110
I told them you were busy.
So, I can just--

281
00:16:26,360 --> 00:16:28,403
No, no, no. It's fine.
I'll--I'll head over.

282
00:16:28,778 --> 00:16:31,407
Peters says I'm never too busy
to butter up customers,

283
00:16:31,490 --> 00:16:33,075
so, I'll... I'll head over.

284
00:16:33,408 --> 00:16:36,162
OK. Their names
are Janice and Janice.

285
00:16:36,913 --> 00:16:37,746
I'm sorry?

286
00:16:38,121 --> 00:16:40,040
- Janice and Janice. Yeah.
- Two Janices!

287
00:16:40,207 --> 00:16:41,667
Wow! Sounds interesting.

288
00:16:41,918 --> 00:16:45,379
Yeah, well, they kind of freak me out,
but they're very excited to see you.

289
00:16:45,462 --> 00:16:48,006
Oh, OK. Well, tell them
I'm very excited to see them.

290
00:16:48,216 --> 00:16:50,176
- OK. [laughs]
- OK. Thanks.

291
00:16:50,759 --> 00:16:51,844
- I'll head out.
- [Clara] OK.

292
00:16:53,929 --> 00:16:55,472
[inaudible conversation]

293
00:16:56,014 --> 00:16:57,557
[indistinct conversation]

294
00:16:58,893 --> 00:17:00,061
Good afternoon, ladies.

295
00:17:01,895 --> 00:17:03,230
- Hi.
- Hi.

296
00:17:03,313 --> 00:17:04,898
- How are you? Shane.
- Janice.

297
00:17:04,981 --> 00:17:06,608
Janice?
Very nice to meet you, Janice.

298
00:17:06,692 --> 00:17:07,609
And?

299
00:17:08,443 --> 00:17:10,278
- Janice.
- [Shane] You're both Janice?

300
00:17:11,614 --> 00:17:14,951
Wow. He is so smooth.
Isn't he smooth, Clara?

301
00:17:15,242 --> 00:17:16,160
Who?

302
00:17:16,618 --> 00:17:21,749
Oh, sure, pretend you don't know.
I'll play along. Shane!

303
00:17:23,416 --> 00:17:24,335
Hang on a second.

304
00:17:25,044 --> 00:17:29,464
Oh, yeah. I guess he's smooth.

305
00:17:32,384 --> 00:17:33,260
Hi, Mr. Peters.

306
00:17:33,719 --> 00:17:35,346
Hi, Bonnie. Clara? Shall we?

307
00:17:35,429 --> 00:17:36,763
[Clara] Sure. I'll be right there, Hugh.

308
00:17:40,017 --> 00:17:42,728
- Hugh?
- Yeah, that's his name.

309
00:17:43,938 --> 00:17:45,439
Really? I thought it was Peters.

310
00:17:46,273 --> 00:17:49,277
You thought he went by mister,
and then his first name?

311
00:17:49,402 --> 00:17:51,278
OK, don't change the subject.

312
00:17:51,444 --> 00:17:54,115
What's he mean, "Shall we?"
Shall we what?

313
00:17:54,615 --> 00:17:57,617
Shall we mind our own business,
maybe? [chuckles]

314
00:18:02,789 --> 00:18:04,125
Mr. Hugh?

315
00:18:10,172 --> 00:18:13,009
All right, guys. Why don't we
take a little bit of a break?

316
00:18:13,174 --> 00:18:14,551
Right? We've got a busy night.

317
00:18:15,094 --> 00:18:16,429
Cool. Good work.

318
00:18:18,138 --> 00:18:19,307
Thank you.

319
00:18:21,642 --> 00:18:23,477
Chef, very nice on the fryer, by the way.

320
00:18:23,685 --> 00:18:24,644
[man] Thanks, chef!

321
00:18:27,147 --> 00:18:28,732
OK, enough about the schedule.

322
00:18:28,816 --> 00:18:30,692
- Yeah.
- I want to talk to you about this project.

323
00:18:31,109 --> 00:18:32,068
What he have...

324
00:18:32,569 --> 00:18:35,197
- [slurping]
- [Shane humming]

325
00:18:38,159 --> 00:18:41,244
- A little soda on the rocks.
- Thank you.

326
00:18:44,498 --> 00:18:47,167
So, you're pretty smooth
over there with your lady fans.

327
00:18:47,250 --> 00:18:49,295
Hmm. Oh, yeah.

328
00:18:49,377 --> 00:18:50,921
They were, uh, they were interesting,

329
00:18:51,005 --> 00:18:53,798
that's for sure. Fun fact,
they're both named Janice.

330
00:18:54,299 --> 00:18:55,675
- [laughs] Wow.
- Yeah.

331
00:18:55,759 --> 00:18:58,804
- That is interesting.
- Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

332
00:18:58,887 --> 00:19:01,641
Well, I bet you have
a lot of lady fans, huh?

333
00:19:01,723 --> 00:19:04,477
Argh! Yeah. I guess. [laughs]

334
00:19:06,019 --> 00:19:07,188
OK, I see

335
00:19:07,270 --> 00:19:08,730
- where this is headed.
- What?

336
00:19:08,814 --> 00:19:10,732
I should probably tell you
I have a boyfriend.

337
00:19:10,816 --> 00:19:11,942
Just to be clear.

338
00:19:12,192 --> 00:19:13,861
- Oh! OK. Yeah, thank--
- Yeah.

339
00:19:13,943 --> 00:19:14,987
- Thank you.
- He is, uh...

340
00:19:15,070 --> 00:19:16,154
a city planner.

341
00:19:16,571 --> 00:19:18,115
- His name is Clive.
- Nice.

342
00:19:18,490 --> 00:19:20,326
You know, Bonnie and Clive.

343
00:19:20,409 --> 00:19:22,744
Like <i>Bonnie and Clyde.</i>
Only instead of Clyde it's...

344
00:19:22,827 --> 00:19:24,163
- Clive.
- Clive. Yeah. [laughs]

345
00:19:25,748 --> 00:19:26,790
I mean, that's lovely.

346
00:19:27,625 --> 00:19:29,042
So, what's up with you and Clara?

347
00:19:29,751 --> 00:19:31,170
You guys been friends
a long time, or what?

348
00:19:31,252 --> 00:19:33,506
Oh, best friends
since we were little kids.

349
00:19:33,588 --> 00:19:34,464
- Oh, really?
- Yeah.

350
00:19:34,548 --> 00:19:36,092
We both grew up here
in Thunder Valley.

351
00:19:36,299 --> 00:19:37,968
I never left, but Clara went to

352
00:19:38,051 --> 00:19:40,471
Chicago for a few years to open up
her own restaurant.

353
00:19:40,805 --> 00:19:42,306
- Oh, really?
- Yeah.

354
00:19:42,390 --> 00:19:43,516
It was a really nice place, too.

355
00:19:43,598 --> 00:19:46,559
It just didn't quite work out
like she planned, you know?

356
00:19:47,144 --> 00:19:50,605
Yeah. Yeah, I mean, you know,
Chicago's a tough market.

357
00:19:52,232 --> 00:19:55,068
But anyways, now she's back,

358
00:19:55,152 --> 00:19:57,779
totally alone,
and no boyfriend to speak of.

359
00:19:58,154 --> 00:19:59,198
[Shane chuckles]

360
00:20:00,615 --> 00:20:01,991
So, there's no city planner then?

361
00:20:02,117 --> 00:20:02,951
- No?
- No.

362
00:20:03,035 --> 00:20:06,163
Yeah. Anyone could just ask her out,
and she'd probably say yes.

363
00:20:06,955 --> 00:20:07,957
OK.

364
00:20:08,582 --> 00:20:10,710
Oh, so, what's going on with her
and Peters over there?

365
00:20:13,503 --> 00:20:15,256
[indistinct conversation]

366
00:20:16,382 --> 00:20:17,298
- Really?
- Yeah.

367
00:20:17,424 --> 00:20:18,718
[Clara laughs]

368
00:20:18,884 --> 00:20:19,801
OK. Now...

369
00:20:20,344 --> 00:20:23,305
Oh! No, there's nothing
going on over there.

370
00:20:23,556 --> 00:20:25,682
- [Clara] Yeah...
- I don't... I don't think.

371
00:21:23,449 --> 00:21:24,532
[door closes]

372
00:22:01,945 --> 00:22:03,948
[footsteps approaching]

373
00:22:11,704 --> 00:22:12,998
[Jackie] They're all one of a kind.

374
00:22:14,750 --> 00:22:15,750
They're gorgeous.

375
00:22:16,751 --> 00:22:17,670
They are.

376
00:22:18,211 --> 00:22:20,756
You should pick your favorite one
and place a bid on it.

377
00:22:21,423 --> 00:22:24,718
You know, every year,
our local artists donate these ornaments,

378
00:22:24,801 --> 00:22:26,886
and then we raffle them off for charity.

379
00:22:27,762 --> 00:22:29,807
That's a tradition started
by Jackie's parents

380
00:22:29,890 --> 00:22:30,807
back in year one.

381
00:22:30,932 --> 00:22:32,351
I see you've met my beautiful wife.

382
00:22:32,684 --> 00:22:33,810
Hi, I'm Jackie.

383
00:22:33,978 --> 00:22:35,770
And I'm the lucky husband, Frank Haven.

384
00:22:35,854 --> 00:22:37,397
[laughing] I'm Shane Roarke.

385
00:22:37,815 --> 00:22:40,317
OK. Shane Roarke.

386
00:22:41,151 --> 00:22:44,529
I'd say, black coffee with half a creamer.

387
00:22:45,072 --> 00:22:48,284
- [Jackie snaps fingers]
- [Frank laughs] Impressed?

388
00:22:48,534 --> 00:22:50,368
Well, young man,
you've seen nothing yet.

389
00:22:51,953 --> 00:22:54,957
Oh, the Mountain View
has been our life for...

390
00:22:55,039 --> 00:22:57,166
- what honey, 22 years?
- Twenty-five years.

391
00:22:57,334 --> 00:22:59,086
Twenty-five years, says the boss.

392
00:22:59,377 --> 00:23:00,671
And believe me, she's always right.

393
00:23:01,547 --> 00:23:04,090
[Jackie] Yes, I am. [chuckles]

394
00:23:04,383 --> 00:23:07,428
So, Shane,
you're not from around here, are you?

395
00:23:08,095 --> 00:23:11,807
No, no. Uh, I'm actually
originally from New York.

396
00:23:12,182 --> 00:23:13,726
- Ah!
- [Shane] And, uh...

397
00:23:13,851 --> 00:23:16,019
I've kind of been roving around
for the last 10 years.

398
00:23:16,103 --> 00:23:19,522
[stammers] And I just took a job over
at the Thunder Mountain resort.

399
00:23:19,940 --> 00:23:23,359
Oh, one of our favorite servers
works up there.

400
00:23:23,527 --> 00:23:25,278
[stutters] It's the Surface, right?

401
00:23:25,778 --> 00:23:27,740
- The Summit.
- Yeah, something like that.

402
00:23:27,823 --> 00:23:30,409
- Yeah.
- [laughs] Her name's Clara Garrison.

403
00:23:31,201 --> 00:23:32,911
Clara. I do know Clara.

404
00:23:32,994 --> 00:23:35,413
She's actually...
she's actually the manager now.

405
00:23:36,039 --> 00:23:37,040
A very good one, at that.

406
00:23:37,249 --> 00:23:40,044
Oh, she's terrific!
She worked here part-time

407
00:23:40,126 --> 00:23:42,296
through high school, and then full-time

408
00:23:42,378 --> 00:23:45,048
for a couple of years
before she went to Chicago.

409
00:23:45,173 --> 00:23:47,009
Jackie and I don't have children
of our own,

410
00:23:47,092 --> 00:23:49,052
so Clara's sort of like a daughter to us.

411
00:23:49,802 --> 00:23:50,887
Right.

412
00:23:51,346 --> 00:23:53,766
So, what brings you from the Summit
to the Mountain View?

413
00:23:54,266 --> 00:23:57,685
Uh... [sighs] history, I guess.

414
00:23:58,604 --> 00:23:59,980
Yeah, I'm kind of...

415
00:24:01,022 --> 00:24:06,278
kind of interested in some of the older,
more family-run resorts in the area.

416
00:24:06,987 --> 00:24:10,199
Well, you've missed the height.
I mean, back in the day,

417
00:24:10,281 --> 00:24:13,576
there were a good dozen or more
just along these mountains.

418
00:24:13,786 --> 00:24:16,121
We're one of the few
that are still scrapping out a living.

419
00:24:16,997 --> 00:24:19,666
It's just so hard to compete
with the big resorts

420
00:24:19,750 --> 00:24:21,292
and the chains anymore, you know.

421
00:24:21,669 --> 00:24:23,545
We still get slammed at breakfast!

422
00:24:23,671 --> 00:24:26,632
Yeah, well, thanks to you.
Without her Eggs Florentine

423
00:24:26,714 --> 00:24:29,134
- we'd be dead and buried by now.
- Really?

424
00:24:30,510 --> 00:24:32,346
You should come by some morning!

425
00:24:33,012 --> 00:24:34,306
Well, I would love that.

426
00:24:53,325 --> 00:24:54,742
[inaudible]

427
00:24:58,705 --> 00:25:01,959
All right. We're still waiting
on one more maple-glazed quail,

428
00:25:02,041 --> 00:25:05,837
a seared trout, and we're going
to do the final beef carpaccio.

429
00:25:29,862 --> 00:25:32,698
- I saw that.
- What look? There was no look.

430
00:25:33,574 --> 00:25:34,866
I didn't say look.

431
00:25:59,307 --> 00:26:00,349
You're still here.

432
00:26:00,851 --> 00:26:04,020
Yeah. Um... I'm just
getting a start on tomorrow.

433
00:26:04,145 --> 00:26:05,230
Nice.

434
00:26:06,481 --> 00:26:08,275
[Shane] Oh, hey, I, um...

435
00:26:09,484 --> 00:26:12,320
I just wanted to say thanks
for helping out tonight.

436
00:26:13,321 --> 00:26:16,825
Oh, yeah, no problem. I mean,
it's better together right?

437
00:26:16,991 --> 00:26:18,493
No, no, no. I know. I know.

438
00:26:18,576 --> 00:26:20,996
But, uh, tonight was crazy busy.
[chuckles]

439
00:26:21,288 --> 00:26:23,499
On top of being
a couple of servers short, so...

440
00:26:23,582 --> 00:26:25,209
- thank you.
- Oh, yeah. Tell me about it.

441
00:26:28,045 --> 00:26:33,424
So, I'm also assuming that you probably
didn't have time for dinner tonight?

442
00:26:35,719 --> 00:26:38,931
No, but that's OK. I can just grab
something on the way home.

443
00:26:39,138 --> 00:26:41,724
Oh, please. What do you mean?
I'm gonna be making something for myself.

444
00:26:41,808 --> 00:26:45,229
You know? I mean, they say
I'm not terrible at this.

445
00:26:45,436 --> 00:26:47,271
- [laughs] That's true. I mean...
- [Shane chuckles]

446
00:26:47,439 --> 00:26:49,316
They actually have been saying
that around here, you know.

447
00:26:49,398 --> 00:26:51,234
- Who's been saying that?
- [both laugh]

448
00:26:52,361 --> 00:26:54,112
- That's a great idea, actually.
- OK.

449
00:26:54,195 --> 00:26:56,573
Um, but you cooked all night.

450
00:26:57,615 --> 00:26:59,034
How about I make us something?

451
00:26:59,826 --> 00:27:01,912
- You?
- Yeah. Yeah.

452
00:27:02,371 --> 00:27:03,538
- All right.
- Yes?

453
00:27:03,622 --> 00:27:04,957
I'm not going to say no to that.

454
00:27:20,012 --> 00:27:20,888
[Shane] Uh!

455
00:27:22,891 --> 00:27:25,394
Are you sure
I can't help with anything?

456
00:27:25,560 --> 00:27:28,605
Well, if you grabbed a bottle of wine,
I wouldn't complain.

457
00:27:29,021 --> 00:27:30,982
- I mean, I can do that. Yeah.
- [laughs] Yeah?

458
00:27:34,862 --> 00:27:37,072
That just smells really good. I just-- OK.

459
00:27:37,154 --> 00:27:38,365
- I got this.
- All right.

460
00:27:53,881 --> 00:27:54,714
[Shane] Wow!

461
00:27:55,590 --> 00:27:56,842
That was fantastic.

462
00:27:57,593 --> 00:27:58,719
Well, thank you.

463
00:27:59,344 --> 00:28:02,431
You know, they say
I'm not terrible at this.

464
00:28:02,513 --> 00:28:05,726
Mm. [chuckles] I mean, I heard that.

465
00:28:06,058 --> 00:28:07,644
- [laughs]
- Bonnie told me

466
00:28:07,728 --> 00:28:10,855
that you, uh, [clears throat]
had your own place.

467
00:28:11,480 --> 00:28:13,107
- [Clara] She did, huh?
- Mm-hmm.

468
00:28:15,861 --> 00:28:16,694
[Clara] Well...

469
00:28:17,820 --> 00:28:20,865
that turned out to be
a little girl's dream that got too big.

470
00:28:22,075 --> 00:28:24,661
At least you did it, right?

471
00:28:25,494 --> 00:28:26,954
I mean, most people
just sit around dreaming.

472
00:28:28,332 --> 00:28:30,917
Think. Imagine how proud
that little girl would have been

473
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:32,169
if she saw what you did?

474
00:28:34,421 --> 00:28:35,547
Pretty proud.

475
00:28:37,507 --> 00:28:39,968
No, I took on more than I could handle.

476
00:28:40,801 --> 00:28:42,304
Maybe it was just bad timing.

477
00:28:42,887 --> 00:28:44,765
And, I doubt it.

478
00:28:46,892 --> 00:28:47,976
Yeah, maybe.

479
00:28:49,478 --> 00:28:51,771
Either way, here I am, back at home,

480
00:28:51,855 --> 00:28:55,567
trying to... figure out what's next.

481
00:28:56,817 --> 00:29:00,655
Huh! I mean,
I think chocolate cake's next.

482
00:29:01,155 --> 00:29:04,116
- [chuckles] Chocolate cake?
- Mm-hmm.

483
00:29:04,201 --> 00:29:07,371
Well, that was my other dream.
So, how did you know?

484
00:29:07,954 --> 00:29:09,248
You wanted to be a chocolate cake?

485
00:29:09,330 --> 00:29:10,915
Yeah, that's exactly what I wanted.

486
00:29:10,999 --> 00:29:12,625
[both laugh]

487
00:29:19,840 --> 00:29:22,719
Thanks for the company tonight.
It was-- It was really great.

488
00:29:23,679 --> 00:29:26,138
Well, it was my pleasure.
And thank you for cooking.

489
00:29:30,685 --> 00:29:34,940
So... [clears throat]
Can I walk you to your car?

490
00:29:36,942 --> 00:29:41,947
My car... Um, well, it's, uh,
it's currently in the shop.

491
00:29:42,447 --> 00:29:47,326
And, uh, the last bus
left about an hour ago.

492
00:29:47,868 --> 00:29:51,373
So, I've been trying to come up
with like a clever way

493
00:29:51,455 --> 00:29:53,000
to ask for a ride.

494
00:29:54,041 --> 00:29:55,501
I will give you a ride. Yeah.

495
00:29:55,794 --> 00:29:56,752
[Clara] Thanks.

496
00:29:59,131 --> 00:30:00,089
[Clara chuckles]

497
00:30:13,311 --> 00:30:14,395
This is it!

498
00:30:14,938 --> 00:30:18,232
Wow. It's a gorgeous building.

499
00:30:19,401 --> 00:30:20,527
How long have you lived here?

500
00:30:21,028 --> 00:30:25,156
I managed to pick it up
with what I had left after Chicago, so...

501
00:30:26,074 --> 00:30:28,785
I am impressed, Ms. Clara Garrison.

502
00:30:29,411 --> 00:30:33,080
With what? The fact
that I'm not homeless? Or...

503
00:30:33,164 --> 00:30:34,875
- [both laugh]
- Hey, I live in a hotel

504
00:30:35,083 --> 00:30:37,085
and all my belongings are in suitcases,

505
00:30:37,169 --> 00:30:38,252
- so...
- [Clara laughs]

506
00:30:39,171 --> 00:30:42,257
So, you are definitely amazing.

507
00:30:44,634 --> 00:30:45,885
[both laugh nervously]

508
00:31:03,194 --> 00:31:06,823
Wow, I can't believe
I'm kissing a celebrity.

509
00:31:12,537 --> 00:31:13,497
What's wrong?

510
00:31:13,579 --> 00:31:16,458
[stammers] Nothing, nothing, nothing.
I--I just don't-- I don't know

511
00:31:16,540 --> 00:31:18,335
if this is the best idea.

512
00:31:21,046 --> 00:31:22,506
I just get a lot of attention

513
00:31:22,588 --> 00:31:24,590
from the show.
I didn't even know you watched it.

514
00:31:24,673 --> 00:31:27,176
I don't. I don't watch your show.

515
00:31:28,761 --> 00:31:31,765
I was just saying I'm surprised.

516
00:31:33,224 --> 00:31:34,683
Like, in a good way.
I feel really stupid--

517
00:31:34,768 --> 00:31:37,186
Hang on, hang on. I don't think
I'm explaining this right,

518
00:31:37,395 --> 00:31:39,021
- but--
- You're definitely not. You--

519
00:31:39,314 --> 00:31:40,356
Good night, Shane.

520
00:31:43,484 --> 00:31:44,903
- [sights]
- [car door closes]

521
00:31:47,864 --> 00:31:49,281
[exhales]

522
00:31:51,242 --> 00:31:52,618
I am such a jerk.

523
00:32:16,308 --> 00:32:17,810
[inaudible]

524
00:32:30,531 --> 00:32:31,615
Two milks, one sugar.

525
00:32:31,700 --> 00:32:33,660
Thank you. You're a lifesaver.

526
00:32:34,243 --> 00:32:35,996
- Are you ready for this morning?
- Hmm...

527
00:32:37,247 --> 00:32:39,290
let me get halfway through
this coffee, and I will be.

528
00:32:40,208 --> 00:32:41,167
Good.

529
00:32:44,045 --> 00:32:45,005
You all right?

530
00:32:47,173 --> 00:32:50,759
Yeah. Yeah, I'm fine.
Uh, I'm just ready.

531
00:32:51,552 --> 00:32:52,386
[Hugh] OK.

532
00:32:53,888 --> 00:32:55,265
- It's just up here.
- [Clara] Great.

533
00:33:00,103 --> 00:33:01,730
- There you go. Enjoy.
- [man] Thank you.

534
00:33:01,813 --> 00:33:03,522
Jackie! Sorry to bother you.

535
00:33:04,273 --> 00:33:05,608
Listen, Frank was right.

536
00:33:06,526 --> 00:33:08,778
Those were the best Eggs Florentine
I have ever had.

537
00:33:08,862 --> 00:33:10,196
[chuckles] Really?

538
00:33:10,321 --> 00:33:12,531
Ever. And I happen
to be an expert on eggs.

539
00:33:12,824 --> 00:33:13,700
Are you, now?

540
00:33:13,950 --> 00:33:16,744
Just a little bit. And I'm gonna have
to get that recipe from you.

541
00:33:16,827 --> 00:33:19,538
I taste the smoked cayenne,
but is that mustard powder in there?

542
00:33:20,207 --> 00:33:21,583
You must put a little pinch--

543
00:33:21,665 --> 00:33:25,420
Whoa, whoa, whoa! I'm afraid
that is a trade secret.

544
00:33:25,503 --> 00:33:27,713
- [both laugh]
- OK, I'm not gonna ask.

545
00:33:28,048 --> 00:33:29,132
[Jackie] More coffee?

546
00:33:29,508 --> 00:33:32,093
Actually, I... I should get going to work.

547
00:33:32,176 --> 00:33:33,427
Well, could I grab a coffee to go?

548
00:33:33,511 --> 00:33:34,930
- Of course.
- Actually,

549
00:33:35,262 --> 00:33:37,390
can I get two coffees to go, please?

550
00:33:38,391 --> 00:33:40,769
- Coming right up.
- [Shane] Thank you.

551
00:33:58,537 --> 00:33:59,746
That's Shane's car, isn't it?

552
00:34:00,955 --> 00:34:02,249
[Clara] Uh, I don't know.

553
00:34:12,342 --> 00:34:13,802
[indistinct chatter]

554
00:34:18,139 --> 00:34:19,641
[chairs clattering]

555
00:34:20,432 --> 00:34:21,559
Hi.

556
00:34:21,934 --> 00:34:24,521
- Well, aren't we lucky to find you here!
- [Shane] Janice, Janice. Hi.

557
00:34:25,271 --> 00:34:27,606
You know ladies, I...
I was actually just on my way out.

558
00:34:27,690 --> 00:34:28,525
- Oh, come on.
- Yeah.

559
00:34:28,608 --> 00:34:30,527
Are you too good
for a second breakfast?

560
00:34:30,943 --> 00:34:32,778
- [both laugh and squeal]
- [door bell jingles]

561
00:34:33,280 --> 00:34:34,947
[indistinct conversation]

562
00:34:37,826 --> 00:34:39,536
- So...
- What'd you have for breakfast?

563
00:34:40,327 --> 00:34:42,496
[stammers] Uh, I did the Eggs Florentine.

564
00:34:42,956 --> 00:34:46,251
- [Jackie] Clara! How good to see you!
- Jackie! Aw!

565
00:34:46,835 --> 00:34:49,378
I always save a hug for Frank.

566
00:34:49,628 --> 00:34:50,547
- [Frank] Hi!
- Hi!

567
00:34:50,963 --> 00:34:52,465
Jackie, Frank. This is Hugh Peters.

568
00:34:52,548 --> 00:34:53,800
He owns the restaurant I work at.

569
00:34:54,217 --> 00:34:56,677
Oh, that's right.
[stutters] The something or other.

570
00:34:56,927 --> 00:34:58,722
- [Hugh] The Summit.
- [Frank] Yeah, sounds about right.

571
00:34:58,804 --> 00:35:00,764
- Yeah.
- [laughing] It's a pleasure to meet you.

572
00:35:02,224 --> 00:35:04,603
Clara, you were right.
This place is charming.

573
00:35:04,893 --> 00:35:07,438
Guys, could we get
a couple minutes after breakfast?

574
00:35:07,938 --> 00:35:09,773
We have a proposal
we'd like to run by you.

575
00:35:10,108 --> 00:35:13,235
A proposal! I haven't had one
of those since Frank's.

576
00:35:13,360 --> 00:35:14,195
Turned out pretty good.

577
00:35:14,528 --> 00:35:16,114
- [Clara laughs]
- [Frank] I pay her to say that.

578
00:35:16,197 --> 00:35:17,615
- [all laugh]
- Just sit down,

579
00:35:17,699 --> 00:35:19,659
and--and we'll be with you
right after the rush, OK?

580
00:35:19,784 --> 00:35:21,702
- [Hugh] Can wait. Can wait.
- OK. Would you like coffee?

581
00:35:21,786 --> 00:35:22,829
[both] Yes, please.

582
00:35:23,829 --> 00:35:25,081
- [Hugh] This way.
- [Clara] Thank you.

583
00:35:33,172 --> 00:35:34,257
[women giggling]

584
00:35:34,423 --> 00:35:37,635
Uh, [stammers] it's so nice
to see you guys again.

585
00:35:37,719 --> 00:35:38,969
- [Janice] Really?
- [Shane] Really. Yeah.

586
00:35:39,179 --> 00:35:40,972
You're-- Huh, no, no, I... [chuckles]

587
00:35:41,056 --> 00:35:42,641
- So, you're a Pisces and we're...
- [Shane] I am.

588
00:35:42,724 --> 00:35:44,559
- [Janice continues indistinctly]
- Hmm.

589
00:35:44,851 --> 00:35:46,226
[Shane] What month is Pisces?

590
00:35:46,311 --> 00:35:47,853
[Frank] All right.
This will get you started.

591
00:35:47,936 --> 00:35:48,938
- [Clara] Thank you.
- [Frank] OK.

592
00:35:49,021 --> 00:35:49,898
[Shane] June is Gemini.

593
00:35:50,773 --> 00:35:52,483
So, if you could eat 10 pounds of food
what'd it be?

594
00:35:52,817 --> 00:35:55,612
Ten pounds?
Uh... probably wings.

595
00:35:56,153 --> 00:35:56,987
What is it?

596
00:35:57,905 --> 00:35:58,739
Nothing.

597
00:36:00,909 --> 00:36:02,284
[indistinct conversation]

598
00:36:02,534 --> 00:36:03,994
I figured you might be hungry.

599
00:36:04,204 --> 00:36:06,539
- Aw. Thank you.
- Thank you.

600
00:36:10,126 --> 00:36:12,545
Wow, you were right, Clara.
This smells incredible.

601
00:36:12,628 --> 00:36:13,505
I told you.

602
00:36:17,132 --> 00:36:18,009
Dig in.

603
00:36:18,967 --> 00:36:22,472
You know, ladies. I, um,
I actually really do have to go.

604
00:36:23,472 --> 00:36:24,391
Oh, great idea!

605
00:36:24,474 --> 00:36:26,601
- We're moving the party, Janice.
- OK. One car or two, Shane?

606
00:36:27,393 --> 00:36:30,146
- I, uh...
- One, two. We'll figure it out!

607
00:36:30,230 --> 00:36:31,648
- Yeah. OK.
- Oh! OK.

608
00:36:31,773 --> 00:36:33,483
[indistinct conversation]

609
00:36:35,275 --> 00:36:36,443
Oh, honey.

610
00:36:39,905 --> 00:36:43,076
- So, we'll see you again soon.
- I-- I'll be back before you know it.

611
00:36:43,326 --> 00:36:44,494
I hope so.

612
00:36:44,952 --> 00:36:46,954
If you guys have any questions,
please call me.

613
00:36:47,038 --> 00:36:49,248
I'd be happy to go over anything
to help you decide.

614
00:36:49,873 --> 00:36:51,918
I'll look at it, and then
Jackie will make the decision.

615
00:36:52,001 --> 00:36:54,211
Oh, come on. Not just me!

616
00:36:54,378 --> 00:36:57,047
Lovely meeting you both.
Hope to hear from you soon.

617
00:36:58,132 --> 00:37:00,802
If our Clara's involved,
I'm sure it'll work out.

618
00:37:01,969 --> 00:37:04,054
[Jackie] Oh, that reminds me.

619
00:37:04,639 --> 00:37:06,766
We met somebody else
who works at the resort.

620
00:37:06,849 --> 00:37:07,726
Oh, yeah. Shawn.

621
00:37:07,809 --> 00:37:09,268
- What--What was his last name?
- It's not Shawn.

622
00:37:09,351 --> 00:37:11,646
It's Shane. Shane Roarke.

623
00:37:11,730 --> 00:37:12,771
That sounds about right. Yeah.

624
00:37:12,896 --> 00:37:14,773
Oh, so, he was just here for breakfast?

625
00:37:15,400 --> 00:37:17,025
No, actually he came by yesterday.

626
00:37:17,943 --> 00:37:18,902
Oh!

627
00:37:21,280 --> 00:37:24,659
Anyway, thank you both, so much.
I'll see you soon.

628
00:37:24,742 --> 00:37:26,577
- Have a good time, darling. Bye.
- Bye-bye.

629
00:37:28,204 --> 00:37:31,583
- Shawn? Shane. Shane. Damn!
- No. It was Shane!

630
00:37:36,295 --> 00:37:39,257
Everybody! As you know,
tonight the restaurant will be closed

631
00:37:39,340 --> 00:37:40,884
for our annual charity dinner.

632
00:37:40,967 --> 00:37:42,635
It's all in the spirit
of Christmas, of course,

633
00:37:42,719 --> 00:37:45,096
but if it happens to throw
a little publicity our way,

634
00:37:45,512 --> 00:37:46,347
so, be it.

635
00:37:46,472 --> 00:37:47,389
[whispering] Don't look now,

636
00:37:47,474 --> 00:37:50,518
but someone's throwing you
some major eye attention.

637
00:37:53,938 --> 00:37:55,023
Let's do some good!

638
00:37:58,985 --> 00:38:00,487
...like when you play basketball,

639
00:38:00,737 --> 00:38:02,864
you might play hard. Use some elbow.

640
00:38:03,072 --> 00:38:03,907
Ah, yeah.

641
00:38:03,989 --> 00:38:04,907
You should go on them easier.

642
00:38:12,039 --> 00:38:13,248
[cell phone beeps]

643
00:38:13,333 --> 00:38:14,541
Call Clara.

644
00:38:17,503 --> 00:38:19,213
[cell phone rings]

645
00:38:19,547 --> 00:38:22,257
- Hey, Mom, you're on speaker.
- Hi, Mrs. Garrison.

646
00:38:22,884 --> 00:38:25,637
Hello, Bonnie, darling.
Clara, I've called to remind you

647
00:38:25,719 --> 00:38:26,971
<i>of our family Christmas dinner.</i>

648
00:38:27,179 --> 00:38:29,974
Yes, it is on my radar
and scheduled in.

649
00:38:30,307 --> 00:38:32,476
Will you be bringing someone
other than Bonnie this year?

650
00:38:33,644 --> 00:38:35,855
Actually, Clive and I
are doing Christmas this year.

651
00:38:36,648 --> 00:38:37,981
Good for you!

652
00:38:38,315 --> 00:38:40,275
Mom, you know I'm too busy to date.

653
00:38:40,360 --> 00:38:42,320
So, you're down one Bonnie
and stuck with me.

654
00:38:42,402 --> 00:38:43,403
[Lydia] <i>Mm.</i>

655
00:38:43,570 --> 00:38:45,949
I seem to recall your baby sister
making time for Barry

656
00:38:46,240 --> 00:38:48,784
<i>- while she was at Harvard.</i>
- Mom!

657
00:38:48,952 --> 00:38:50,869
I'm just saying. Just saying.

658
00:38:52,038 --> 00:38:52,956
Mom, I've got to go.

659
00:38:53,373 --> 00:38:55,708
- All right. Just be on time.
- [Clara] <i>I will.</i>

660
00:38:55,791 --> 00:38:57,293
- Bye.
- [Clara] <i>Bye.</i>

661
00:38:59,295 --> 00:39:00,128
Nice.

662
00:39:00,922 --> 00:39:03,715
[Bonnie laughs] Got to love it.

663
00:39:03,800 --> 00:39:04,800
[Clara] Mm-hmm.

664
00:39:34,496 --> 00:39:35,873
Perfect. Thank you.

665
00:39:38,835 --> 00:39:40,961
I managed to sneak you
another chocolate raspberry truffle.

666
00:39:41,045 --> 00:39:43,505
Oh, you devil. Oh, it's so good.

667
00:39:43,590 --> 00:39:45,215
- Thank you.
- [Clara] My pleasure.

668
00:39:45,550 --> 00:39:47,217
The food is better than ever this year.

669
00:39:47,510 --> 00:39:48,802
Well, we have a new chef.

670
00:39:49,137 --> 00:39:52,764
Oh, fantastic! Honestly, though,
the best part isn't the food.

671
00:39:52,849 --> 00:39:54,057
The best part is seeing you guys again.

672
00:39:54,516 --> 00:39:55,434
[both] Aw.

673
00:39:55,518 --> 00:39:57,394
- We look forward to seeing you every year.
- Oh, it's so nice.

674
00:39:57,478 --> 00:39:58,271
Yeah.

675
00:39:58,438 --> 00:40:00,188
So, are you seeing anyone?

676
00:40:01,065 --> 00:40:02,483
- [Hugh] Clara!
- Speaking of seeing...

677
00:40:03,150 --> 00:40:04,193
[Clara] I'll be right back.

678
00:40:06,278 --> 00:40:08,489
I would love for you to meet
my rock star manager Clara.

679
00:40:08,572 --> 00:40:10,324
She is one of a kind.

680
00:40:10,407 --> 00:40:11,909
- [male guest] Clara.
- Nice to meet you.

681
00:40:12,159 --> 00:40:14,411
- Clara, nice to meet you.
- Are you having a great time?

682
00:40:16,331 --> 00:40:17,623
[indistinct conversation]

683
00:40:18,625 --> 00:40:20,460
I'll just gonna check in the kitchen,
and make sure everything is OK.

684
00:40:20,543 --> 00:40:21,460
- Absolutely.
- Great. I'll be back.

685
00:40:29,719 --> 00:40:31,179
And I'm an idiot.

686
00:40:44,275 --> 00:40:45,777
Clara? [clears throat]

687
00:40:46,485 --> 00:40:47,487
Yeah?

688
00:40:49,280 --> 00:40:51,407
Do you mind if I just have a quick word?

689
00:40:54,159 --> 00:40:56,244
I saw you at the Mountain View
this morning...

690
00:40:56,913 --> 00:40:58,789
with those two girls that came in.

691
00:40:59,289 --> 00:41:02,501
[laughs] No, no. OK, I don't know
what you think you saw,

692
00:41:02,585 --> 00:41:04,003
- but it definitely wasn't--
- Hey,

693
00:41:04,836 --> 00:41:06,922
- you don't need to explain yourself to me.
- No, no, I was just eating,

694
00:41:07,005 --> 00:41:09,092
and they forced me to sit with them.
I didn't have a choice.

695
00:41:09,342 --> 00:41:11,135
Yeah, you looked really trapped.

696
00:41:12,637 --> 00:41:14,889
Argh. I don't--I don't want to fight.

697
00:41:15,639 --> 00:41:18,393
I really just came over
to talk to you about the other night.

698
00:41:19,978 --> 00:41:20,978
Please.

699
00:41:24,106 --> 00:41:25,817
Thank you. I...

700
00:41:28,193 --> 00:41:30,195
I wanted to talk to you about, um...

701
00:41:32,407 --> 00:41:34,617
your car. Uh, has...

702
00:41:34,784 --> 00:41:37,077
has the mechanic
gotten back to you at all?

703
00:41:38,913 --> 00:41:42,916
Yeah. It was a problem
with the alternator.

704
00:41:43,418 --> 00:41:45,585
- It'll be ready in a few days.
- OK, great.

705
00:41:46,545 --> 00:41:49,382
Uh, I mean, not--not great.
But I was wondering

706
00:41:49,465 --> 00:41:51,134
if--if you... needed a...

707
00:41:52,135 --> 00:41:54,052
I was gonna offer to take you home

708
00:41:54,344 --> 00:41:56,472
- after work tonight-- OK. Right.
- I'm good.

709
00:41:59,307 --> 00:42:02,186
I guess Mr. Peters can give you
a ride home then?

710
00:42:04,230 --> 00:42:06,356
- You know, Shane...
- Yeah?

711
00:42:06,440 --> 00:42:10,152
However I decide to get to work,
whether I walk or take the bus,

712
00:42:10,235 --> 00:42:11,320
or get a ride with Peters,

713
00:42:11,403 --> 00:42:14,865
- is really none of your business.
- You know, I know, I know. You're right.

714
00:42:14,949 --> 00:42:15,867
You're right-- right, of course.

715
00:42:15,949 --> 00:42:20,288
Look. Please. This isn't... [chuckles]
this isn't how I saw this going.

716
00:42:20,371 --> 00:42:22,998
I just...
Can you just let me explain

717
00:42:23,206 --> 00:42:24,791
why I got freaked out the other night?

718
00:42:25,293 --> 00:42:28,755
That's not necessary
because you were pretty clear.

719
00:42:28,838 --> 00:42:30,047
No, I wasn't. Look...

720
00:42:30,840 --> 00:42:33,717
a celebrity chef isn't something
I ever saw myself becoming.

721
00:42:34,010 --> 00:42:35,887
And I... I misjudged you rudely,

722
00:42:36,387 --> 00:42:39,014
and I just really
would like to be able to...

723
00:42:39,347 --> 00:42:41,016
explain myself properly.

724
00:42:43,143 --> 00:42:44,144
Would you...

725
00:42:45,438 --> 00:42:47,356
would you want--want to
come back to my place

726
00:42:47,940 --> 00:42:48,900
after we're done here tonight?

727
00:42:50,443 --> 00:42:52,487
Because you--you cooked for me. Right?

