980
00:58:58,744 --> 00:59:00,454
Of course. Of course they trust you.

981
00:59:01,996 --> 00:59:03,331
But do you trust Peters?

982
00:59:06,168 --> 00:59:08,378
Why are you being so negative about this?

983
00:59:09,503 --> 00:59:10,838
I thought you'd be happy for me.

984
00:59:10,922 --> 00:59:12,257
No, no, no, it's not that
I'm not happy for you.

985
00:59:12,340 --> 00:59:13,842
I'm happy for you. I'm just...

986
00:59:14,925 --> 00:59:18,472
Look, when I first took the job here,
I made a couple of calls.

987
00:59:19,097 --> 00:59:22,059
And Hugh doesn't exactly have

988
00:59:22,141 --> 00:59:23,518
- the best reputation.
- [Clara scoffs]

989
00:59:24,226 --> 00:59:25,186
What?

990
00:59:27,146 --> 00:59:29,733
So, you can sign a big fat deal with him,
and I can't?

991
00:59:29,858 --> 00:59:32,985
No, I just work for the guy.
All right? It's only temporary.

992
00:59:34,653 --> 00:59:36,572
[scoffs] I'm so glad I told you this.

993
00:59:36,655 --> 00:59:39,367
Clara, I'm sorry. It's not...
it's not what I mean. I'm just saying...

994
00:59:40,034 --> 00:59:43,663
that whatever he tells you
about this property

995
00:59:43,746 --> 00:59:48,376
or anything, you--you can't just assume
it to be true, right?

996
00:59:48,460 --> 00:59:50,045
You got to take it with a grain of salt.

997
00:59:50,170 --> 00:59:51,128
[Clara sighs]

998
00:59:52,130 --> 00:59:54,048
But did you ever think
maybe this is all happening

999
00:59:54,132 --> 00:59:55,592
because I'm actually good at my job?

1000
00:59:55,675 --> 00:59:56,592
[Shane] No, you are!

1001
00:59:56,927 --> 00:59:58,344
You're most certainly good at your job,

1002
00:59:58,427 --> 01:00:00,304
but I'm just saying
you might still have blinders on

1003
01:00:00,387 --> 01:00:01,764
because of what happened
to you in Chicago.

1004
01:00:03,391 --> 01:00:05,393
OK, I'm sorry. That's not...
that's not what I meant.

1005
01:00:05,476 --> 01:00:08,146
What I meant to say is he might not be
being honest with you.

1006
01:00:08,188 --> 01:00:09,606
And I just want to look out for you.

1007
01:00:10,065 --> 01:00:11,108
OK?

1008
01:00:12,442 --> 01:00:14,902
I told you this
because I was really excited.

1009
01:00:15,820 --> 01:00:18,364
I don't need your approval.
I can take care of myself.

1010
01:00:18,447 --> 01:00:20,449
Clara, listen! Clara! Please!

1011
01:00:21,076 --> 01:00:22,159
Merry Christmas.

1012
01:00:49,186 --> 01:00:52,023
[Lydia] Oh, she is just the cutest!

1013
01:00:52,106 --> 01:00:53,608
Does she have her daddy's eyes or what?

1014
01:00:53,942 --> 01:00:55,902
- [Darlene] Yes, she does.
- [Lydia and Barry laugh]

1015
01:00:57,362 --> 01:00:58,947
I just want to say how thankful I am

1016
01:00:59,030 --> 01:01:02,074
to have all of our loved ones
together for Christmas.

1017
01:01:02,159 --> 01:01:03,367
Yes, baby.

1018
01:01:04,202 --> 01:01:06,663
This was always
your father's favorite time of year,

1019
01:01:06,746 --> 01:01:08,123
and not just because of the slopes!

1020
01:01:09,166 --> 01:01:12,168
But nothing made him happier
than having us all together.

1021
01:01:13,836 --> 01:01:16,380
Maybe next year we'll have a full house.
Right, Clara?

1022
01:01:16,672 --> 01:01:18,842
[all laugh]

1023
01:01:19,050 --> 01:01:20,010
I'm kidding.

1024
01:01:20,760 --> 01:01:21,677
To family.

1025
01:01:21,969 --> 01:01:23,387
[all] To family!

1026
01:01:24,181 --> 01:01:25,472
[Lydia] Cheers!

1027
01:01:30,978 --> 01:01:33,231
Darlene, would you lead us in prayer?

1028
01:01:33,356 --> 01:01:34,608
- I'd love to.
- OK.

1029
01:01:36,860 --> 01:01:38,737
Dear Lord,
thank you for bringing us together

1030
01:01:38,820 --> 01:01:39,778
during this special time.

1031
01:01:40,280 --> 01:01:42,072
For blessing us
with all this delicious food

1032
01:01:42,157 --> 01:01:44,326
to nourish our bodies.
In the Lord's name,

1033
01:01:44,784 --> 01:01:45,827
- Amen.
- [all] Amen!

1034
01:01:45,911 --> 01:01:46,869
[Lydia] Thank you, darling.

1035
01:01:47,119 --> 01:01:48,371
All right, let's dig in.

1036
01:01:48,746 --> 01:01:50,706
Barry, would you do us the honors?

1037
01:01:50,789 --> 01:01:51,916
- Yes, I would.
- [Lydia] Thank you.

1038
01:01:53,835 --> 01:01:55,545
[Lydia coddles, chuckles]

1039
01:01:55,836 --> 01:01:57,213
[Lydia] So, Darlene,

1040
01:01:57,297 --> 01:01:58,797
any exciting new cases?

1041
01:01:58,965 --> 01:02:01,300
I just started a new case.
It's been very busy. Yes.

1042
01:02:01,592 --> 01:02:04,429
So, I can't say too much about it
right now, but, yeah.

1043
01:02:04,596 --> 01:02:06,222
[Lydia] And where are my pictures
of the baby?

1044
01:02:06,306 --> 01:02:08,516
[Darlene] We--We have one for you.
Don't you worry.

1045
01:02:08,599 --> 01:02:11,894
Yeah. We got lots of photos.
So, yeah.

1046
01:02:12,061 --> 01:02:13,438
- It's good.
- [Lydia] I'm so proud of you.

1047
01:02:21,528 --> 01:02:23,657
[Lydia] Oh,
I really outdid myself this year.

1048
01:02:23,739 --> 01:02:25,699
- [Clara] You did!
- [Lydia laughs]

1049
01:02:26,159 --> 01:02:28,452
Lydia, I've been meaning to ask.
How did your photo shoot go

1050
01:02:28,536 --> 01:02:30,871
- for your gingerbread house?
- Ah, it was for <i>Seasons Magazine.</i>

1051
01:02:30,956 --> 01:02:32,916
It went amazing, you know.

1052
01:02:32,998 --> 01:02:35,001
Personally,
I think I should be on the cover!

1053
01:02:35,126 --> 01:02:36,585
[all laugh]

1054
01:02:36,753 --> 01:02:38,170
Or at least like a two-page spread.

1055
01:02:38,295 --> 01:02:39,172
- [Barry] Yeah.
- Centerfold.

1056
01:02:39,380 --> 01:02:40,840
- [Barry] Yeah.
- [Clara] You know what, I'm just gonna...

1057
01:02:40,923 --> 01:02:44,594
I'm just going to clear this
out of the way for everyone.

1058
01:02:44,885 --> 01:02:46,137
- [Lydia] Thank you, Clara.
- Thanks.

1059
01:02:46,221 --> 01:02:48,097
- Yeah. Excuse me, Barry.
- Mm-hmm.

1060
01:02:50,684 --> 01:02:52,559
So, um, how are things at work?

1061
01:02:52,643 --> 01:02:55,021
- [Barry] Oh, it's going really well.
- [Lydia] Really well? Good. Yeah.

1062
01:02:55,521 --> 01:02:57,440
[chatting continues]

1063
01:03:04,155 --> 01:03:06,032
[phone rings]

1064
01:03:10,786 --> 01:03:13,164
Well, hello, Clara!
Merry Christmas Eve.

1065
01:03:13,623 --> 01:03:14,498
Clive says hi.

1066
01:03:14,581 --> 01:03:15,875
- Clive! Say hi!
- Hi.

1067
01:03:16,751 --> 01:03:17,751
Hi, Clive.

1068
01:03:17,876 --> 01:03:20,255
[Bonnie] OK, s <i>o, how was the meal?</i>
<i>How's the family?</i>

1069
01:03:21,338 --> 01:03:22,298
You know.

1070
01:03:22,965 --> 01:03:24,967
My favorite couple doing so well.

1071
01:03:25,302 --> 01:03:26,302
It's, uh...

1072
01:03:27,052 --> 01:03:30,389
amazing, and it's absolutely killing me.
[chuckles]

1073
01:03:31,307 --> 01:03:32,474
Do you want to meet for a drink?

1074
01:03:32,809 --> 01:03:34,268
Uh, yeah, of course.

1075
01:03:34,351 --> 01:03:36,688
Well, let me just check with Clive.

1076
01:03:37,105 --> 01:03:39,065
Is it OK if I meet Clara for a drink?

1077
01:03:39,440 --> 01:03:40,858
- Yup.
- Clive says yup.

1078
01:03:41,525 --> 01:03:44,362
OK, great. I'll meet you--
I'll meet you there.

1079
01:03:45,405 --> 01:03:46,447
OK. Bye.

1080
01:03:47,865 --> 01:03:50,492
Thanks, babe. See you later.

1081
01:03:54,371 --> 01:03:55,331
[sighs]

1082
01:03:55,414 --> 01:03:58,376
- Hey, honey. Everything OK?
- Hey.

1083
01:03:59,293 --> 01:04:01,338
Yeah. Everything's fine.

1084
01:04:03,005 --> 01:04:04,423
Mom, do you think, um...

1085
01:04:04,715 --> 01:04:06,675
It'd be OK for you
to go have a drink with Bonnie?

1086
01:04:07,217 --> 01:04:09,219
- Yeah.
- [laughs] Sure.

1087
01:04:09,971 --> 01:04:10,929
Thank you.

1088
01:04:12,766 --> 01:04:15,434
You know, honey, things can change

1089
01:04:15,518 --> 01:04:19,230
from one Christmas to the next.
I'm just saying. [chuckles]

1090
01:04:21,483 --> 01:04:22,317
Thank you, Mom.

1091
01:04:22,733 --> 01:04:23,735
You're welcome.

1092
01:04:24,652 --> 01:04:25,820
[Clara sighs]

1093
01:04:29,114 --> 01:04:30,115
Now, go have fun.

1094
01:04:30,657 --> 01:04:32,994
- OK. I'll see you after.
- [Lydia chuckles]

1095
01:04:40,376 --> 01:04:41,460
- [hostess] Hi.
- Hey.

1096
01:04:41,543 --> 01:04:42,420
How are you doing?

1097
01:04:51,804 --> 01:04:53,306
[Bonnie] Thanks for the drink!

1098
01:04:54,474 --> 01:04:55,641
[Clara] No problem.

1099
01:04:56,684 --> 01:04:57,684
[laughs]

1100
01:05:00,063 --> 01:05:01,188
Thank you for coming.

1101
01:05:02,398 --> 01:05:03,817
I wouldn't miss it for the world.

1102
01:05:05,693 --> 01:05:06,777
- Hey, Mike!
- [Mike] Yeah?

1103
01:05:06,860 --> 01:05:08,655
- How about a couple of drinks?
- [Mike] Sure, no problem.

1104
01:05:08,737 --> 01:05:11,324
Christmas... can be a difficult time.

1105
01:05:13,534 --> 01:05:14,619
[Mike] Yeah. Here you go.

1106
01:05:15,536 --> 01:05:17,163
- Thanks, Mike.
- [Mike] You're welcome.

1107
01:05:18,289 --> 01:05:21,501
To best friends and better days.

1108
01:05:22,418 --> 01:05:24,086
- Cheers.
- [glasses clinking]

1109
01:05:29,217 --> 01:05:33,637
It's just like everyone
was so... happy.

1110
01:05:34,222 --> 01:05:36,474
My sister with her perfect husband,

1111
01:05:36,557 --> 01:05:38,643
and he's just equally happy with her.

1112
01:05:38,726 --> 01:05:41,019
And they're both incredibly happy
with their child.

1113
01:05:41,103 --> 01:05:42,230
I mean, it was just...

1114
01:05:42,646 --> 01:05:44,858
I'm telling you, Bonnie, it was horrible!

1115
01:05:45,650 --> 01:05:48,110
I'm really sorry to hear
about all that happiness.

1116
01:05:48,193 --> 01:05:50,070
- That sucks.
- Right?

1117
01:05:54,367 --> 01:05:56,786
Well, I'm afraid
I have some happy news?

1118
01:05:57,244 --> 01:05:58,163
What?

1119
01:06:03,418 --> 01:06:04,668
[Bonnie] I'm engaged!

1120
01:06:07,505 --> 01:06:09,507
- [gasps] Oh, Bonnie!
- [Bonnie giggles]

1121
01:06:11,842 --> 01:06:13,635
- Congratulations.
- Thank you!

1122
01:06:15,554 --> 01:06:16,722
- Oh, you're crying?
- No.

1123
01:06:16,806 --> 01:06:18,224
Of course not. I'm not. I'm not.

1124
01:06:18,599 --> 01:06:20,559
- You are.
- No, I'm-- They're happy tears.

1125
01:06:20,643 --> 01:06:22,519
- They're, uh...
- They don't look happy.

1126
01:06:22,603 --> 01:06:25,148
They're happy. I'm happy.
I'm so happy for you!

1127
01:06:26,983 --> 01:06:28,233
When are you gonna do it?

1128
01:06:28,568 --> 01:06:30,320
I don't know. Maybe in the spring.

1129
01:06:30,402 --> 01:06:32,947
Or... [scoffs] a few years from now.

1130
01:06:33,239 --> 01:06:35,532
It depends on how long it takes me
to make my own dress.

1131
01:06:36,284 --> 01:06:37,452
I don't even know how to sew.

1132
01:06:41,289 --> 01:06:43,458
My best friend is getting married.

1133
01:06:44,541 --> 01:06:46,251
To a terrific Clive.

1134
01:06:47,545 --> 01:06:51,007
And I've fallen for a guy

1135
01:06:52,342 --> 01:06:55,677
who may not be that guy.
Or he may be that guy

1136
01:06:55,762 --> 01:06:57,096
and I just wrecked everything,

1137
01:06:57,179 --> 01:07:00,099
and I may never even see that guy again.

1138
01:07:01,226 --> 01:07:02,101
Except at work.

1139
01:07:03,436 --> 01:07:04,603
At the restaurant.

1140
01:07:05,230 --> 01:07:07,440
And just five days a week.

1141
01:07:08,690 --> 01:07:09,858
More with overtime.

1142
01:07:10,818 --> 01:07:14,614
Yeah. [sighs]
I'm-- I'm going to quit my job.

1143
01:07:15,114 --> 01:07:16,407
[Bonnie] Well, that's a great idea.

1144
01:07:18,742 --> 01:07:20,452
[cell phone rings]

1145
01:07:23,706 --> 01:07:26,583
Hey, Hugh.
How's... how's your Christmas?

1146
01:07:26,876 --> 01:07:28,710
- [children giggling]
- No, the ex-wife dropped off the kids,

1147
01:07:28,795 --> 01:07:30,922
unannounced, and I'm just trying
to get some work done.

1148
01:07:31,505 --> 01:07:34,259
Oh, that... sounds... fun!

1149
01:07:34,675 --> 01:07:36,844
Uh, look. I need you to go to the office

1150
01:07:36,927 --> 01:07:38,387
and pick up something for me, please.

1151
01:07:39,097 --> 01:07:40,389
Uh, yeah, sure. No problem.

1152
01:07:40,472 --> 01:07:43,726
I am totally capable
of doing that right now.

1153
01:07:44,686 --> 01:07:47,605
Good. There are documents
in a manila envelope on my desk.

1154
01:07:47,688 --> 01:07:49,356
I'd get them myself, but I'm stuck here.

1155
01:07:49,440 --> 01:07:51,568
Oh, yeah. Sure. No problem.
I'll... I'll pick them up

1156
01:07:51,650 --> 01:07:53,318
and swing by first thing in the morning.

1157
01:07:53,402 --> 01:07:55,862
- See you then.
- Yes, you will!

1158
01:07:55,947 --> 01:07:57,114
No, no, no. No more cookies.

1159
01:07:57,197 --> 01:07:58,074
- No, thatâs enough.
- [children continue giggling]

1160
01:07:58,157 --> 01:08:00,284
I gotta go. I got to parent here.

1161
01:08:00,994 --> 01:08:04,079
- No, seriously. That's five. We're done.
- [children giggling]

1162
01:08:06,958 --> 01:08:08,418
What was that about?

1163
01:08:09,001 --> 01:08:10,253
It's a secret!

1164
01:08:10,335 --> 01:08:12,922
I get told secrets now. No big deal.

1165
01:08:13,880 --> 01:08:16,259
Well, you can tell me, too!

1166
01:08:17,260 --> 01:08:18,427
Peters just left some paperwork

1167
01:08:18,511 --> 01:08:20,054
at the restaurant
that I have to go pick up.

1168
01:08:21,096 --> 01:08:22,599
Well, I am in!

1169
01:08:23,682 --> 01:08:24,559
Well...

1170
01:08:25,268 --> 01:08:27,060
This is my fourth glass,
so, I can't drive.

1171
01:08:27,145 --> 01:08:28,145
- [Clara chuckles]
- Ah!

1172
01:08:29,396 --> 01:08:30,773
I'll get Clive to drive!

1173
01:09:10,188 --> 01:09:11,773
Clive, this is where I work.

1174
01:09:18,195 --> 01:09:20,782
- All right. Come on in.
- [Bonnie] Whoa!

1175
01:09:20,989 --> 01:09:21,908
Hugh's office.

1176
01:09:22,492 --> 01:09:24,409
Really nice. I like it.

1177
01:09:26,412 --> 01:09:27,704
OK, what are we looking for again?

1178
01:09:27,872 --> 01:09:30,667
A yellow envelope. Like this.

1179
01:09:32,918 --> 01:09:34,503
[cabinet drawer clunking]

1180
01:09:35,962 --> 01:09:38,173
Honey, I... I think that might be locked.

1181
01:09:38,256 --> 01:09:39,591
No, it's just stuck.

1182
01:09:40,760 --> 01:09:41,802
B-Bonnie, I...

1183
01:09:44,764 --> 01:09:46,306
- See!
- [Clara] Bonnie, I...

1184
01:09:46,932 --> 01:09:47,809
I got it.

1185
01:09:48,559 --> 01:09:49,476
Me too!

1186
01:09:49,644 --> 01:09:52,270
I probably think it's this one
that was on his desk

1187
01:09:52,354 --> 01:09:54,189
exactly where he told me
it was gonna be.

1188
01:09:54,273 --> 01:09:57,443
Well, this is yellow as well,
so, I think it deserves a look.

1189
01:09:58,569 --> 01:10:01,655
This is a...
Oh, this is Shane's contract.

1190
01:10:04,574 --> 01:10:05,702
That's a lot of zeros.

1191
01:10:07,369 --> 01:10:08,912
This one's just a lot of parking lots.

1192
01:10:10,747 --> 01:10:11,707
What?

1193
01:10:12,166 --> 01:10:14,418
- Pretty boring!
- [Clara] Oh...

1194
01:10:14,502 --> 01:10:17,671
Oh, no, no.
This is, uh... this is just our, uh...

1195
01:10:19,215 --> 01:10:20,048
What?

1196
01:10:22,342 --> 01:10:23,636
You've got to be kidding me.

1197
01:10:24,470 --> 01:10:25,680
What? Is it about me?

1198
01:10:26,805 --> 01:10:28,140
Clive, you're a city planner, right?

1199
01:10:28,682 --> 01:10:30,059
Correct. Why?

1200
01:10:32,270 --> 01:10:33,688
Because we need to go to your office.

1201
01:10:35,230 --> 01:10:36,983
- Yay! Oh, my gosh.
- No, no, no.

1202
01:10:37,065 --> 01:10:38,067
- Yes!
- We don't do that.

1203
01:10:38,150 --> 01:10:39,359
- Oh, we're going!
- Or-- You know what?

1204
01:10:40,987 --> 01:10:42,113
- [Jackie] Aw.
- [Frank] Here.

1205
01:10:42,195 --> 01:10:44,698
Ah, you know, we forgot
to share the mistletoe.

1206
01:10:45,574 --> 01:10:47,493
That's because
we don't need any mistletoe.

1207
01:10:47,577 --> 01:10:48,869
- [Frank] Hmm. We don't.
- [knocking at the door]

1208
01:10:48,953 --> 01:10:49,787
Shoot. Who's it?

1209
01:10:51,913 --> 01:10:53,373
[Frank] Hey! Look who came in

1210
01:10:53,457 --> 01:10:55,917
- from the cold. Come here!
- [Jackie] Merry Christmas, Shane!

1211
01:10:56,002 --> 01:10:56,918
[Shane] Merry Christmas.

1212
01:10:57,170 --> 01:10:58,546
[Jackie] Aw! Oh!

1213
01:10:59,296 --> 01:11:02,048
- I'm not intruding at all, am I?
- No, of course not.

1214
01:11:02,175 --> 01:11:04,342
Absolutely not! You know
we love guests at Christmas.

1215
01:11:05,261 --> 01:11:06,095
OK.

1216
01:11:07,180 --> 01:11:10,349
Oh! You look like you could use
something to eat.

1217
01:11:10,432 --> 01:11:14,479
How about I make you a nice sandwich,
or Frank can make you a drink?

1218
01:11:17,314 --> 01:11:18,483
I'd love a sandwich.

1219
01:11:19,024 --> 01:11:20,234
OK, you got it.

1220
01:11:21,527 --> 01:11:22,987
- Thanks, honey.
- Thanks, Jackie.

1221
01:11:24,279 --> 01:11:26,032
Come on. Take your jacket off.
Make yourself at home.

1222
01:11:26,948 --> 01:11:28,618
- Thanks so much.
- You're welcome.

1223
01:11:30,494 --> 01:11:32,537
[indistinct conversation]

1224
01:11:32,704 --> 01:11:34,247
- [Clara] Bonnie!
- This is great.

1225
01:11:34,873 --> 01:11:36,833
This is so exciting!

1226
01:11:37,167 --> 01:11:38,252
[Clive] I don't know why I'm doing this.

1227
01:11:38,543 --> 01:11:39,796
- This is insane.
- Come on. Please, Clive.

1228
01:11:39,878 --> 01:11:42,631
You're doing it because
it's an exciting secret mission.

1229
01:11:43,632 --> 01:11:44,966
And because you love me.

1230
01:11:45,801 --> 01:11:47,177
Get in. Get in. Quietly.

1231
01:11:47,761 --> 01:11:48,845
[inaudible]

1232
01:11:57,729 --> 01:11:58,980
- But we love him.
- Yeah.

1233
01:12:01,775 --> 01:12:02,693
When I first came here,

1234
01:12:02,777 --> 01:12:04,737
I didn't--I didn't tell you guys
what I was looking for.

1235
01:12:04,820 --> 01:12:06,154
And I didn't... didn't show you this.

1236
01:12:08,740 --> 01:12:09,867
Aw.

1237
01:12:09,951 --> 01:12:11,743
[Shane] That's my parents
on their honeymoon.

1238
01:12:13,412 --> 01:12:16,748
Yeah, that picture hung up in our kitchen
for as long as I can remember.

1239
01:12:17,542 --> 01:12:19,210
They never really said where they took it,

1240
01:12:19,292 --> 01:12:21,503
and I didn't really ask
because I was a kid.

1241
01:12:21,671 --> 01:12:24,548
But they said it was somewhere
in the American mountainside,

1242
01:12:24,631 --> 01:12:27,760
and that one day they'd...
they'd visit again.

1243
01:12:28,886 --> 01:12:30,637
But--But they--they never did.

1244
01:12:32,347 --> 01:12:34,516
And you think they stayed here?

1245
01:12:35,309 --> 01:12:36,143
[Shane] I don't know.

1246
01:12:37,060 --> 01:12:38,229
I don't know. I kind of...

1247
01:12:38,311 --> 01:12:40,398
You know, I've been ruling out
some of the other places in the area,

1248
01:12:40,480 --> 01:12:44,527
but most of them have been
torn down or long closed.

1249
01:12:45,069 --> 01:12:49,614
Yeah. I'm so sorry.
I don't recognize them at all.

1250
01:12:50,574 --> 01:12:53,661
Of course, this doesn't mean anything
because when this photo was taken

1251
01:12:53,743 --> 01:12:55,371
my parents would've been
running the place,

1252
01:12:55,453 --> 01:12:56,956
and I would've just been a little kid.

1253
01:12:57,038 --> 01:12:59,625
- But, honey, I do recognize that cushion.
- Hmm.

1254
01:12:59,917 --> 01:13:01,918
Yeah, yeah.
That's--That's the one right over there.

1255
01:13:02,002 --> 01:13:04,838
Yeah, but the trouble is these cushions
are all over the place, you know.

1256
01:13:06,215 --> 01:13:07,091
Right.

1257
01:13:07,966 --> 01:13:09,676
I--I don't know if it helps,
but on the back

1258
01:13:09,760 --> 01:13:12,012
- is a... a date stamped there.
- Hmm.

1259
01:13:12,345 --> 01:13:14,765
- Oh, in the 80's.
- Oh! Yeah, yeah, yeah.

1260
01:13:15,349 --> 01:13:18,269
You see, we had a fire here in '92,

1261
01:13:18,935 --> 01:13:20,854
and it destroyed almost all the records.

1262
01:13:20,938 --> 01:13:23,983
Otherwise, we could've looked up
their names in the log book.

1263
01:13:24,442 --> 01:13:26,694
[Shane] Right. Yeah, I was...

1264
01:13:28,029 --> 01:13:30,030
I was just hoping to find
that ornament, but...

1265
01:13:31,282 --> 01:13:32,699
if it were here, you guys probably...

1266
01:13:33,242 --> 01:13:34,784
probably auctioned it off anyways.

1267
01:13:34,868 --> 01:13:35,744
[Frank] Yeah.

1268
01:13:35,828 --> 01:13:36,746
[Jackie] Whoa!

1269
01:13:37,954 --> 01:13:40,957
- What?
- Wait, wait, wait a minute.

1270
01:13:41,626 --> 01:13:43,920
Wait. Here, check this out.
Here, take this. Take this.

1271
01:13:44,002 --> 01:13:44,962
OK.

1272
01:13:50,216 --> 01:13:51,469
Oh, there's no way.

1273
01:14:17,662 --> 01:14:19,079
I thought you guys would've...

1274
01:14:19,913 --> 01:14:20,997
I thought...

1275
01:14:23,333 --> 01:14:24,710
I thought you guys would've sold these.

1276
01:14:24,793 --> 01:14:28,463
Well... yes, we would've,
but not that one.

1277
01:14:28,756 --> 01:14:30,298
That one is special.

1278
01:14:30,382 --> 01:14:33,511
That one my mother made the year
they built this place.

1279
01:14:34,095 --> 01:14:37,264
And every Christmas Eve we have
our guests put it on the tree.

1280
01:14:38,515 --> 01:14:41,476
So, if your parents stayed here
over Christmas...

1281
01:14:42,353 --> 01:14:45,730
they would've been asked
to do the honors.

1282
01:14:46,106 --> 01:14:47,608
It's our way of making our guests

1283
01:14:47,692 --> 01:14:49,443
feel like they're family
at Christmas time.

1284
01:14:54,948 --> 01:14:56,283
[sobs]

1285
01:14:59,787 --> 01:15:00,954
So, they were here.

1286
01:15:02,456 --> 01:15:03,666
They were here.

1287
01:15:05,542 --> 01:15:06,836
[Frank] So, Shane...

1288
01:15:08,628 --> 01:15:10,922
would you like to do the honors?

1289
01:15:18,471 --> 01:15:19,515
You know, I...

1290
01:15:20,599 --> 01:15:24,353
I'd actually like to share this
with someone.

1291
01:15:24,936 --> 01:15:26,021
If that's OK.

1292
01:15:32,903 --> 01:15:34,488
[voice breaking] Thank you for this.

1293
01:15:45,750 --> 01:15:46,792
Did you find it yet?

1294
01:15:47,960 --> 01:15:49,252
I literally just started looking!

1295
01:15:49,462 --> 01:15:52,172
It's, uh... Peters. Hugh Peters.
- [Bonnie scoffs]

1296
01:15:52,797 --> 01:15:55,176
- [Bonnie] Hugh.
- Oh. OK, here it is.

1297
01:15:56,135 --> 01:15:58,470
It looks like he's made
some exploratory proposals.

1298
01:16:01,140 --> 01:16:02,015
What?

1299
01:16:03,016 --> 01:16:04,018
[Bonnie] What is it?

1300
01:16:04,601 --> 01:16:08,980
It's just a bunch of condos,
or parking lots, and...

1301
01:16:09,398 --> 01:16:10,815
Wait, this is not what we talked about.

1302
01:16:10,899 --> 01:16:12,318
- I don't understand what this is.
- [Clive] Let me take these

1303
01:16:12,400 --> 01:16:13,277
and make a copy.

1304
01:16:13,527 --> 01:16:14,569
You can read them in the morning, Clara.

1305
01:16:15,320 --> 01:16:16,529
And then you are gonna destroy them.

1306
01:16:17,030 --> 01:16:18,990
And then we'll pretend
that this never happened. OK?

1307
01:16:20,826 --> 01:16:21,659
OK.

1308
01:16:22,161 --> 01:16:23,496
- All right.
- [Clara] Thank you.

1309
01:16:25,372 --> 01:16:27,875
I love you guys! Bonnie and Clive!

1310
01:16:28,042 --> 01:16:28,876
[all chuckle]

1311
01:16:28,958 --> 01:16:32,171
- We're criminals!
- [Clive] Oh, heaven help me.

1312
01:16:32,253 --> 01:16:33,213
[all chuckle]

1313
01:16:45,935 --> 01:16:48,104
[Lydia humming a Christmas song]

1314
01:16:53,067 --> 01:16:55,277
Oh, Merry Christmas, sunshine.

1315
01:16:56,028 --> 01:16:58,238
Merry Christmas, Mom. Thank you.

1316
01:16:58,780 --> 01:17:01,699
Oh. Someone had
a little bit too much fun last night.

1317
01:17:01,951 --> 01:17:02,868
Mm-hmm.

1318
01:17:03,118 --> 01:17:03,993
[Lydia chuckles]

1319
01:17:08,039 --> 01:17:08,957
[sighs]

1320
01:17:12,586 --> 01:17:13,587
Where'd you find these?

1321
01:17:14,171 --> 01:17:15,421
They were scattered in the foyer.

1322
01:17:20,677 --> 01:17:21,554
I--

1323
01:17:23,264 --> 01:17:25,306
[Lydia continues humming]

1324
01:17:27,434 --> 01:17:28,769
I can't believe he did this.

1325
01:17:29,060 --> 01:17:32,189
How about a bagel and lox?

1326
01:17:36,193 --> 01:17:37,153
A Bloody Mary?

1327
01:17:40,573 --> 01:17:42,533
[Clara] Mom, I'm so sorry.

1328
01:17:43,408 --> 01:17:45,911
I promise I'll be back, OK?
I just have to do something.

1329
01:17:46,078 --> 01:17:47,037
No breakfast?

1330
01:17:51,750 --> 01:17:52,960
[car approaching]

1331
01:18:19,403 --> 01:18:20,237
[knocking on door]

1332
01:18:20,404 --> 01:18:21,613
[Hugh] Yeah, I'm coming!

1333
01:18:29,121 --> 01:18:29,997
Clara.

1334
01:18:30,497 --> 01:18:33,167
- Did you get the folder?
- Oh, you mean Shane's contract? Yes.

1335
01:18:33,500 --> 01:18:34,460
Thanks. I have to get these off
this morning.

1336
01:18:34,542 --> 01:18:35,502
And there's this!

1337
01:18:36,878 --> 01:18:38,463
You don't want to renovate
the Mountain View.

1338
01:18:38,922 --> 01:18:40,757
You don't want to "restore it
to its former glory".

1339
01:18:40,841 --> 01:18:41,884
You want to tear it down

1340
01:18:42,091 --> 01:18:44,511
for condos, and concessions
and parking lots!

1341
01:18:44,595 --> 01:18:46,721
[Hugh] These are just
exploratory proposals.

1342
01:18:48,140 --> 01:18:49,307
Where did you get these?

1343
01:18:49,515 --> 01:18:51,935
You used me
to get to Frank and Jackie.

1344
01:18:51,976 --> 01:18:53,645
[Hugh] And you couldn't even
get that done.

1345
01:18:54,520 --> 01:18:56,774
They called me this morning
to tell me that the deal is dead.

1346
01:18:57,274 --> 01:19:00,277
Yeah, it turns out your boyfriend Shane
convinced them to shut it down.

1347
01:19:00,903 --> 01:19:02,070
I never should've trusted that guy.

1348
01:19:02,154 --> 01:19:04,239
He's not my boyfriend.
And Shane's in New York.

1349
01:19:04,323 --> 01:19:05,240
[Hugh snickers]

1350
01:19:05,407 --> 01:19:06,492
Is that--Is that what he said?

1351
01:19:07,117 --> 01:19:10,453
Yeah, it looks like Santa's flying past
both of our houses this Christmas.

1352
01:19:11,079 --> 01:19:13,832
Yeah, well, you can take
your stupid necklace back, too.

1353
01:19:17,711 --> 01:19:19,212
I hope you realize you're fired!

1354
01:19:19,505 --> 01:19:21,090
Oh, I quit!

1355
01:19:30,640 --> 01:19:32,685
[engine turning over]

1356
01:19:40,900 --> 01:19:41,694
Come on!

1357
01:19:42,194 --> 01:19:43,487
- [knocking on the car]
- What?

1358
01:19:43,654 --> 01:19:44,697
[Shane] Merry Christmas.

1359
01:19:47,740 --> 01:19:48,783
Can I give you a ride?

1360
01:19:52,704 --> 01:19:53,622
[chuckles] Come on.

1361
01:19:57,960 --> 01:20:00,296
[railroad crossing
bells blaring]

1362
01:20:07,344 --> 01:20:09,220
[train whistling in the distance]

1363
01:20:10,972 --> 01:20:12,807
- [Shane] It's a long train.
- [sighs]

1364
01:20:14,560 --> 01:20:15,810
How did you even find me?

1365
01:20:17,604 --> 01:20:19,898
I went to your mother's house.

1366
01:20:21,442 --> 01:20:24,153
Well, she told me
that you were at Bonnie and Clive's.

1367
01:20:24,235 --> 01:20:25,945
And so I went there and, um...

1368
01:20:26,904 --> 01:20:29,283
I mean, they told me about
your little crime spree last night.

1369
01:20:29,574 --> 01:20:32,536
And then I kind of figured out
where you might be headed.

1370
01:20:33,328 --> 01:20:34,787
Look, I know it sounds crazy,

1371
01:20:34,872 --> 01:20:36,832
but I went to the office,
there were two envelopes and--

1372
01:20:36,914 --> 01:20:38,375
[Shane] I didn't come here for the job.

1373
01:20:41,295 --> 01:20:43,380
I came here because
I was looking for something,

1374
01:20:43,505 --> 01:20:45,131
that promise that I made to myself.

1375
01:20:46,507 --> 01:20:48,301
And that's why I went
to the Mountain View.

1376
01:20:50,054 --> 01:20:51,721
And that's why I was there last night.

1377
01:21:03,399 --> 01:21:04,359
These are my parents.

1378
01:21:09,155 --> 01:21:13,243
Their honeymoon was the one and only
vacation that they ever took.

1379
01:21:16,704 --> 01:21:18,623
You know, they lived in New York City,
and they could...

1380
01:21:19,291 --> 01:21:21,167
they could barely make ends meet, so...

1381
01:21:23,002 --> 01:21:24,296
it was really difficult for them.

1382
01:21:25,046 --> 01:21:27,925
My father was a cook at a greasy spoon.

1383
01:21:28,007 --> 01:21:29,217
My mother was a server.

1384
01:21:30,594 --> 01:21:32,095
And as a kid I saw...

1385
01:21:33,639 --> 01:21:36,766
I saw how hard they struggled
in their careers, you know.

1386
01:21:39,144 --> 01:21:40,395
[chuckles] But I guess that's...

1387
01:21:41,270 --> 01:21:43,231
that's where I developed
my love for cooking.

1388
01:21:46,902 --> 01:21:50,279
When I started to get successful
I promised them that I'd slow down

1389
01:21:51,030 --> 01:21:52,908
and find myself a beautiful little spot

1390
01:21:52,990 --> 01:21:54,952
like the one
that started them off so right.

1391
01:21:57,829 --> 01:21:59,247
But I--I didn't.

1392
01:22:03,335 --> 01:22:05,503
Three years ago,
my mother died of cancer.

1393
01:22:07,965 --> 01:22:11,385
Another year later, my father suffered
a massive heart attack.

1394
01:22:15,180 --> 01:22:18,934
So, here I am... [sighs]
three years too late,

1395
01:22:19,851 --> 01:22:21,979
trying to make good
on a promise to a family

1396
01:22:22,061 --> 01:22:23,771
that I didn't even deserve.

1397
01:22:25,440 --> 01:22:27,693
You know any family
would be lucky to have you.

1398
01:22:30,945 --> 01:22:32,029
That's really sweet.

1399
01:22:35,451 --> 01:22:38,537
Now, come on.
I want to show you something.

1400
01:22:52,551 --> 01:22:55,011
[geese honking in the distance]

1401
01:23:17,868 --> 01:23:18,784
[Shane] Come on in.

1402
01:23:20,203 --> 01:23:21,913
[both] Merry Christmas!

1403
01:23:23,539 --> 01:23:25,542
- Merry Christmas.
- Merry Christmas.

1404
01:23:25,751 --> 01:23:28,170
Dinner will be served
in the main dining room

1405
01:23:28,212 --> 01:23:29,337
in a few minutes.

1406
01:23:39,597 --> 01:23:42,643
I would actually like to give you
your Christmas present.

1407
01:23:54,570 --> 01:23:55,988
It's just like the picture.

1408
01:23:56,323 --> 01:23:58,283
Mm-hmm.
Well, would you do the honors?

1409
01:24:00,911 --> 01:24:01,787
Please?

1410
01:24:16,467 --> 01:24:17,344
[Frank] Gotcha!

1411
01:24:24,893 --> 01:24:28,104
That's the most thoughtful gift
anyone could ever give me.

1412
01:24:28,521 --> 01:24:29,730
Oh, that's not your gift.

1413
01:24:30,565 --> 01:24:33,484
- What?
- No, no. This is your gift.

1414
01:24:41,076 --> 01:24:42,786
It took me a long time to figure out

1415
01:24:42,868 --> 01:24:44,704
what I wanted to do
for the rest of my life.

1416
01:24:47,832 --> 01:24:49,835
But when the picture
brought me to you...

1417
01:24:51,627 --> 01:24:56,007
I knew that this... [chuckles]
this was the right choice.

1418
01:25:06,976 --> 01:25:08,854
Jackie and Frank
have agreed to sell their hotel.

1419
01:25:11,148 --> 01:25:12,231
But only to you.

1420
01:25:17,362 --> 01:25:18,654
Shane, I can't afford that.

1421
01:25:18,738 --> 01:25:20,032
I want to invest...

1422
01:25:21,533 --> 01:25:23,493
solely in your business, Clara...

1423
01:25:25,746 --> 01:25:26,954
because you deserve it.

1424
01:25:29,123 --> 01:25:30,458
You can fix this place up

1425
01:25:32,043 --> 01:25:33,170
any way you want.

1426
01:25:34,587 --> 01:25:36,297
Jackie and Frank have agreed

1427
01:25:37,131 --> 01:25:38,591
to stick around and work for you.

1428
01:25:39,676 --> 01:25:41,302
I mean, I'd like to hand in my resume

1429
01:25:41,470 --> 01:25:43,387
for the head chef, of course,
and do all the cooking...

1430
01:25:45,724 --> 01:25:47,309
minus the Eggs Florentine.

1431
01:25:51,896 --> 01:25:53,105
But you don't have to hire me.

1432
01:25:55,317 --> 01:25:56,943
You don't have to do anything
you don't want...

1433
01:26:00,404 --> 01:26:01,657
because it's all yours.

1434
01:26:08,579 --> 01:26:09,706
Can it be ours?

1435
01:26:18,297 --> 01:26:19,298
I love you.

1436
01:26:21,342 --> 01:26:22,301
I love you.

1437
01:26:40,444 --> 01:26:41,279
You should know...

1438
01:26:42,447 --> 01:26:43,989
I just got you a scarf.

1439
01:26:44,949 --> 01:26:46,784
[laughing] That's just what I wanted.

1440
01:26:53,875 --> 01:26:55,085
Merry Christmas.

1441
01:26:57,128 --> 01:26:58,630
Merry Christmas.

1442
01:27:05,177 --> 01:27:07,514
- Merry Christmas.
- Merry Christmas.

1443
01:27:13,185 --> 01:27:14,438
[TV reporter] <i>A nine-year-old metro girl</i>

1444
01:27:14,520 --> 01:27:15,604
- <i>got a new lease on life...</i>
- [Clive] Hey, Bonnie.

1445
01:27:16,021 --> 01:27:18,899
So, my friend Mario
is a liftie over at the gondola.

1446
01:27:19,234 --> 01:27:22,154
And he says he could sneak us
up the mountain for a late night ski.

1447
01:27:22,820 --> 01:27:23,654
You want to go?

1448
01:27:24,488 --> 01:27:27,701
You mean another exciting mission? Yes!

1449
01:27:27,783 --> 01:27:30,244
- See! I knew you weren't boring.
- [Clive chuckles]

1450
01:27:30,828 --> 01:27:32,122
All right! Let's go do this.

1451
01:27:32,913 --> 01:27:34,666
- Now? Oh, OK!
- Right now! Right now!

1452
01:27:36,542 --> 01:27:38,670
This is your Grandma's favorite.
She loves it.

1453
01:27:40,796 --> 01:27:42,798
- She loves her Auntie Clara.
- [Clara chuckles]

1454
01:27:44,509 --> 01:27:45,719
That's a pretty dress!

1455
01:27:45,969 --> 01:27:46,927
[Lydia] Shane!

1456
01:27:47,636 --> 01:27:50,181
There you are.
I've been meaning to talk to you.

1457
01:27:51,766 --> 01:27:53,018
I've been watching your show.

1458
01:27:54,853 --> 01:27:57,898
Uh, Ms. Garrison,
I'm gonna have to explain.

1459
01:27:57,980 --> 01:28:00,859
Uh, you see on the show,
we have these personas.

1460
01:28:00,942 --> 01:28:02,610
- [baby murmuring]
- Yeah, he's not actually that bad.

1461
01:28:02,694 --> 01:28:03,819
Yeah. I'm really not.

